{"key":"post-5599154","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>5599154</id>\n<content>You dunk in the refrigerator to prevent bacteria buildup that would otherwise contaminate your brf if you dunked at room temperature.&amp;nbsp; Don't confuse that with cold shocking, although it does cold shock them...lol&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As for cased bulk substrates, I ran several experiments a few years ago where half the trays were placed in the refrigerator for 24 hours, while the second half were left at room temperature.&amp;nbsp; Both sets of trays went to the fruiting chamber at the same time.&amp;nbsp; Every single tray that had been 'cold shocked' pinned two or more days later than trays that had not been cold shocked.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;That is not to say a temperature change can't be a pinning trigger.&amp;nbsp; However, along with light, a fully colonized substrate, and an increase in air exchange, it is only one of the triggers.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;However, cold shock being beneficial or not, you only need to dunk your cakes in the refrigerator if it's extremely hot during the summer months when there could be a bacteria bloom in the water.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>5599222</next>\n<prev>5599110</prev>\n<first>5599110</first>\n<last>5600966</last>\n<when>1146974714</when>\n<utime>05/07/06 07:05 AM</utime>\n</post>"}